<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-082-026  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 082 026.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 13 1989 n525 p35(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Better SOI wafers: Ibis enhances Simox process.andO;(silicon-on-insulator, Ibis Technology Corp., separation byimplementation of oxygen)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bindra, Ashok.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ibis Technology Corp of Danvers, MA, has significantly improvedthe quality of its silicon-on-insulator (SOI) wafers through majorimprovements in the firm's separation by implantation of oxygen(SIMOX) production process.andP;  Claimed improvements includeincreasing wafer uniformity by a factor of two, reducing defectdensity by a factor of 10 to about 10,000 per square centimeter,and reducing particle by a factor of four.andP;  Ibis says that its SOIwafers are now cost-competitive with ones produced using thezone-melt-recrystallize (ZMR) technique while offering higherquality than ZMR.andP;  SOI wafers offer speed, radiation hardness, andtemperature tolerance comparable to gallium arsenide but withhigher yield and at a lower cost.andP;  The technology is still farmore expensive than bulk silicon and will remain used only inhigh-performance applications for some time.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ibis Technology Corp. (innovations).andO;Topic:     Integrated Circuit FabricationCost ReductionComparisonCost Benefit AnalysisSilicon-On-IsolatorSemiconductor Preparation.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Projected Simox sales. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>